# OfferedPsks.identities lower-bound inconsistency

## 1. Conclusion

This issue concerns the minimum length constraint on `OfferedPsks.identities`.
RFC 8446 requires `identities<7..2^16-1>`, but the current OpenSSL code path does not enforce a unified hard-fail check for this lower bound. Therefore this item is classified as **Partially Satisfied**.

## 2. RFC 8446 English Source Text

### 2.1 `pre_shared_key` extension structure definition

From [RFC 8446 (TLS 1.3), Section 4.2.11](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8446#section-4.2.11):

```text
The "extension_data" field of this extension contains a
"PreSharedKeyExtension" value:

   struct {
       opaque identity<1..2^16-1>;
       uint32 obfuscated_ticket_age;
   } PskIdentity;

   opaque PskBinderEntry<32..255>;

   struct {
       PskIdentity identities<7..2^16-1>;
       PskBinderEntry binders<33..2^16-1>;
   } OfferedPsks;

   struct {
       select (Handshake.msg_type) {
           case client_hello: OfferedPsks;
           case server_hello: uint16 selected_identity;
       };
   } PreSharedKeyExtension;
```

The key constraint is:

```text
PskIdentity identities<7..2^16-1>;
```

### 2.2 Vector syntax lower-bound meaning

From [RFC 8446, Section 3.4](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8446#section-3.4):

```text
Variable-length vectors are defined by specifying a subrange of legal
lengths, inclusively, using the notation <floor..ceiling>.
```

The `7` in `<7..2^16-1>` is the inclusive lower bound on the encoded byte length.

### 2.3 Parse-failure handling semantics

From [RFC 8446, Section 6](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8446#section-6):

```text
Peers which receive a message which cannot be parsed according to the
syntax (e.g., have a length extending beyond the message boundary or
contain an out-of-range length) MUST terminate the connection with a
"decode_error" alert.
```

## 3. OpenSSL Code Description

### 3.1 Reading the identities vector

OpenSSL reads the `identities` vector in `tls_parse_ctos_psk()` in `ssl/statem/extensions_srvr.c`:

```c
if (!PACKET_get_length_prefixed_2(pkt, &identities)) {
    SSLfatal(...);
    return 0;
}
```

### 3.2 Behavior boundary of `PACKET_get_length_prefixed_2`

This API only guarantees that the length prefix can be read and that the byte range does not overflow. It does not enforce the RFC floor value.

### 3.3 Empty identities do not trigger an error in this segment

The subsequent loop condition is:

```c
for (id = 0; PACKET_remaining(&identities) != 0; id++) {
    ...
}
```

When `identities` has length `0` (clearly below the RFC lower bound of 7), the loop body is never entered and no error is raised in this segment.

## 4. Root Cause of Inconsistency

The inconsistency comes from a mismatch between the constraint level in the spec and the check level in the implementation:

1. RFC treats `<floor..ceiling>` as a syntactic validity constraint that includes the lower bound.
2. The OpenSSL path focuses on prefix parsing and memory safety, without a unified `>= 7` hard check on the `identities` vector length.
3. As a result, inputs that are parseable but violate the RFC minimum length can pass through this parsing segment.

## 5. Test Evidence

Runtime output from `runtime_retest/id307/test_psk_identities_lower_bound.out`:

```text
[empty_identities_len0] parse_ok=1 entries=0 zero_len_identity_seen=0
```

When `identities` length is `0`, this parsing path still returns success, which supports the inconsistency conclusion.

OpenSSL Version
OpenSSL 3.5.0 (and likely all 3.x versions with the new record layer)
Platform
Linux (x86_64), TCP sockets
Description
SSL_write() incorrectly returns a positive value (claiming all bytes were written) when the underlying socket send() system call returns 0 with a non-retryable errno. On a subsequent SSL_write() call, the internal assertion check in tls_write_records() detects leftover pending write buffer data and triggers a fatal error (SSL_R_RECORD_LAYER_FAILURE / ERR_R_SHOULD_NOT_HAVE_BEEN_CALLED).
Root Cause Analysis
The bug is in ssl/record/methods/tls_common.c, function tls_retry_write_records() (around line 1932):
```
i = BIO_write(rl->bio, ..., (unsigned int)TLS_BUFFER_get_left(thiswb));
if (i >= 0) {
    tmpwrit = i;
    if (i == 0 && BIO_should_retry(rl->bio))
        ret = OSSL_RECORD_RETURN_RETRY;
    else
        ret = OSSL_RECORD_RETURN_SUCCESS;  /* <-- BUG */
}
```
When send() returns 0 in sock_write() (crypto/bio/bss_sock.c:139):
1. sock_write() returns 0 and does not set the retry flag (errno is non-retryable)
2. BIO_write() returns 0 (i.e. i = 0)
3. Since i >= 0 is true, the code enters the positive branch
4. i == 0 && BIO_should_retry(rl->bio) is false (no retry flag set)
5. The code falls through to ret = OSSL_RECORD_RETURN_SUCCESS — this is wrong
Then at the buffer consumption check (line 1960):
```
if (i >= 0 && tmpwrit == TLS_BUFFER_get_left(thiswb)) {
    /* tmpwrit=0, but buffer still has data -> FALSE */
} else if (i <= 0) {
    /* i=0 -> TRUE */
    return ret;  /* returns OSSL_RECORD_RETURN_SUCCESS */
}
```
tls_retry_write_records() returns OSSL_RECORD_RETURN_SUCCESS even though 0 bytes were actually written. Back in ssl3_write_bytes() (ssl/record/rec_layer_s3.c), the code sees SUCCESS, assumes wpend_tot bytes were fully written, sets *written = tot + wpend_tot (= 100), and returns 1. So SSL_write() returns 100 to the caller.
On the next SSL_write() call, tls_write_records() hits the assertion:
```
if (!ossl_assert(rl->nextwbuf >= rl->numwpipes
                 || TLS_BUFFER_get_left(&rl->wbuf[rl->nextwbuf]) == 0)) {
    RLAYERfatal(rl, SSL_AD_INTERNAL_ERROR, ERR_R_SHOULD_NOT_HAVE_BEEN_CALLED);
    return OSSL_RECORD_RETURN_FATAL;
}
```
The previous write buffer still contains unsent data, so the assert fails and a fatal error is raised.
Reproduction
While send() returning 0 on a TCP socket is unusual on most platforms, it can occur in edge cases (e.g., certain network driver behavior, socket in a transitional state, or via a custom BIO that returns 0 without setting retry). The bug can be reliably reproduced by:
1. Establishing a TLS connection using SSL_connect()/SSL_accept()
2. Mocking or injecting a send() that returns 0 with errno set to a non-retryable value (e.g., EPIPE)
3. Calling SSL_write(ssl, buf, 100)
4. Observing that SSL_write() returns 100 (falsely claiming success)
5. Calling SSL_write() again — this triggers the fatal error
Proposed Fix
In ssl/record/methods/tls_common.c, tls_retry_write_records(), treat BIO_write() returning 0 without the retry flag as a fatal error:
```
if (i >= 0) {
    tmpwrit = i;
    if (i == 0 && BIO_should_retry(rl->bio))
        ret = OSSL_RECORD_RETURN_RETRY;
    else if (i == 0) {
        ERR_raise_data(ERR_LIB_SYS, get_last_sys_error(),
                       "tls_retry_write_records failure");
        ret = OSSL_RECORD_RETURN_FATAL;
    }
    else
        ret = OSSL_RECORD_RETURN_SUCCESS;
}
```
Note on KTLS empty fragment case: This fix is safe for the existing KTLS zero-byte write path. When KTLS sends an empty fragment, tmpwrit == 0 and TLS_BUFFER_get_left(thiswb) == 0, so the subsequent check at line 1965 (tmpwrit == TLS_BUFFER_get_left(thiswb)) evaluates to TRUE and returns OSSL_RECORD_RETURN_SUCCESS before reaching the new i == 0 handling.
Affected Code
- ssl/record/methods/tls_common.c — tls_retry_write_records() (primary bug location)
- crypto/bio/bss_sock.c — sock_write() (returns 0 from send() without distinguishing error)
- ssl/record/rec_layer_s3.c — ssl3_write_bytes() (propagates false success to SSL_write)

